Now we substitute $\sin \theta = \frac{2}{3}$ into the identity:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\cos(2\theta) &= 1 - 2\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2 \\
&= 1 - 2\left(\frac{4}{9}\right) \\
&= 1 - \frac{8}{9} \\
&= \frac{1}{9}
\end{aligned}
$$

Based on the markscheme, you earn one mark for the identity, one for the substitution, and one for the final result.

Substitute the values we found, $\sin \theta = \frac{2}{3}$ and $\cos \theta = \frac{\sqrt{5}}{3}$, into the identity:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\cos(2\theta) &= \left(\frac{\sqrt{5}}{3}\right)^2 - \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2 \\
&= \frac{5}{9} - \frac{4}{9} \\
&= \frac{1}{9}
\end{aligned}
$$

According to the markscheme, showing the attempt to use the formula and substituting the correct values earns the marks.
